english:
  title: Epitaph and Preface for Park Gong, Lord of Milsan, Grand Commandant of High Rank, Meritorious Minister in Quelling the Rebellion and Defending the Realm, Posthumously Titled the Filial and Reverent
  author: Kim Su-nyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lord Milsan Park Gong, whose courtesy name was Gyeongyin, has passed away. As his sons prepared his burial, they requested an epitaph from Kim Su-nyeong of Sangnak, saying: "You in your youth frequented our home and knew our late father best. We beseech you to illuminate his virtue and magnify his achievements that they may endure eternal remembrance." At that time Su-nyeong himself was in mourning for his mother. They embraced and wept together, and though he demurred, they would not accept his refusal.

    Investigating antiquity, the Park clan originated in Silla. A divine being descended from heaven to become the founder of Silla—history records this in detail. His descendants spread throughout the Three Hans, and generation upon generation produced men of renown, but those dwelling in Milsan became most eminent and founded a household of great standing.

    In the waning days of Goryeo there was a Minister of the Board of Rites named Sagyeong, who became the great-grandfather of our Lord. He was a man of benevolence and propriety. Minister Sim was born of him and entered our nation's court to serve our Taejo with merit recorded in the Rolls of Original Merit Ministers, rising to Minister of the Board of Taxation. From the Minister came Ganggang, who gained renown through scholarly grace as Mayor of Anbyon, and was posthumously promoted to Chancellor of the State Council. The Chancellor fathered our Lord's father, named Jeol-mun, a man of steadfast conduct and literary skill. He held office as Corrector in the School of Letters, and through our Lord's virtue received the honorific title "Minister of Pure Loyalty, Accumulated Virtue, and Righteous Conduct" and was posthumously elevated to Left Chancellor.

    Initially, our Lord's mother, the Lady Wang, noble consort of grave propriety, when pregnant dreamed of an ox as large as a house. Astounded, she revealed this to the Chancellor, who said: "When fortune rises, omens appear first. Perhaps this child shall revive our house." He entrusted the Lady with careful nurture before departing this life. Seven months later our Lord was born.

    Bright and luminous, keen and extraordinary, even in youth he shunned frivolous play. As he grew, he of his own accord took up books and learned to read. At fifteen he passed the examination of the National Academy. He then sought out worthy teachers and companions, cultivating learning and refining his writing. In the year Eulmo of the Xuande era, he attained the higher degree.

    Selected as Doctor of the Jiphyeon Academy, he rose to Vice Compiler and Director of Composition. He was then transferred to Censor-Inspector and Left Aide of the Board of Personnel, while taking concurrent charge of the Spring and Autumn Annals. His reputation grew ever greater. At that time the Astronomical Officials were ignorant and unskilled, which troubled the Sejo. The king especially appointed our Lord as Judge of the Astronomical Bureau. Lord Park studied the celestial mechanisms and penetrated their mysteries so thoroughly that no small error escaped his attention. Even veteran astronomers could not surpass him.

    Through successive promotions he became Right Aide of the Board of Personnel while retaining his post as Director of Composition. He was elevated to Advisor of Ceremonial Protocol holding concurrent rank as Associate Minister of the Crown Prince's Household. In the declining years of Sejo, as the king grew weary with illness, all matters save military affairs were referred to the Crown Prince for decision. The administration of the Eastern Palace passed through the Minister's office, and our Lord fulfilled this responsibility so ably that public opinion esteemed him ever more highly.

    Entering the State Council as Inspector of Details, he twice returned to the Censorate as Chief Censor, and a third time as Rectifier of Conduct. During his service in the Censorate, holding firm to elevated standards, he exerted himself vigorously until the court's discipline was restored. When serving in the lower ranks he was dignified and refined, bearing the unmistakable bearing of a future prime minister. Promoted as a capable administrator to concurrently serve as Minister of War, he was soon elevated to Vice President of the Royal Secretariat.

    In the spring of the year Gyeyu of the Jingtan era, the king personally conducted an examination, and our Lord served as Chief Reader. That winter, when the present sovereign quelled the internal rebellion, our Lord, holding a position of crucial importance, united his heart and devoted all his strength to assist and accomplish the task. His counsel proved sound and the matter was achieved—his merit was foremost. He was thus appointed Minister of War and Director of the Royal Lectures. The troubled times required his stabilizing presence. His accomplishments were recorded and he received the honorific "Minister of Meritorious Service in Transmitting Loyalty, Defending the Realm, and Aiding in the Quelling of Rebellion," and was enfeoffed as Lord of Ningchuan. His portrait was painted and reverently preserved in the Archive of Oaths. From the Ministry of War he was transferred to Mayor of Hanseong and again entered the Censorate as Chief Censor.

    He served sequentially as Minister of the Boards of Works, Personnel, Punishment, and Rites, and was reappointed Lord of Milsan. Wherever he served, he grasped the essentials and maintained order without busying himself with petty details. In recommending talent and judging legal cases, he was impartial and never obsequious. In managing great affairs, conducting ceremonies, and performing sacrifices, all was resplendent and worthy of observation. The world called him a worthy prime minister.

    In the spring of the year Bingzi of the Tianshun era, he presided over the civil service examination and was promoted to Vice Premier of the Right. Shortly after he was elevated to Vice Premier of the Left. In the spring of the year Gimyo he again presided over the examinations. In all he conducted three great examinations, bringing forward many renowned scholars. In autumn he suffered the mourning of his mother, the Lady of grave propriety. His grief was so profound that his frame withered to skeletal form. Upon the completion of his period of mourning, he was reappointed Lord of Milsan and elevated in rank to Commandant of Highest Grade.

    On the fifteenth day of the fifth month of summer in the second year of Chenghua, he passed away in his chamber at the age of fifty-five. When word of his death reached the throne, the sovereign was deeply grieved, suspended court business, commanded officials to visit in mourning, granted sacrificial provisions, and bestowed gifts of condolence. His posthumous name was changed to "the Filial and Reverent."

    Our Lord was a sincere and virtuous man, warm and affable in temperament. He constantly grieved that he had not been born while his father lived, his sorrow so deep it seemed to leach the life from him. In serving his mother he was devoted in filial piety, trembling lest he offend her will. To his elder brother he gave the reverence due to heaven itself. In relieving the urgent needs of kinsmen and relations he spared no expense, exhausting his wealth willingly. In managing his property he sought only sufficiency, never desiring excess. Whether in his private quarters or in his social intercourse, his heart remained constant and unchanging, neither ardent nor peculiar in his manner.

    In the conduct of affairs he was capable and at ease, never allowing even the smallest trace of arrogance to show. The more his honors and repute grew, the more his heart humbled itself. Though he held many positions of authority, his gates were never thronged with sycophants. He spent his declining years composing writings to instruct his sons, discoursing on the lessons of extravagance and frugality, success and failure throughout the ages. He also composed a Warning Against Excess and displayed it where he sat, thereby admonishing himself and, through his example, his children. His words, though concise, contained profound meaning and serve as instruction for all the world.

    In the seventh month of that year, with proper observance, he was buried in the northern part of Gyeohwa county at Tanpo in the village of Ogomi, in a separate tomb but the same burial ground as his wife, the Lady of Nampyeong of the Mun clan. She was the daughter of Mun Seung-jo, Right Aide of the Board of Works—pure, beautiful, and virtuous in conduct, a worthy mate to her noble husband and a mother to worthy sons. She preceded him in death.

    They had three sons and two daughters. The eldest son, named Jeon, served as Governor of Bucheon. The second son, named Mi, was Assistant Mayor of Hanseong. The third son, named Geon, was Vice President of the Royal Secretariat. The second and youngest both excelled in letters, passed the examinations, and brought honor to their lineage. The youngest gained the degree in the same year as Su-nyeong. The eldest daughter died before their father. The second daughter married Yu O, Keeper of the Royal Wardrobe.

    The Governor of Bucheon married the daughter of Yun Samsan, Advisor of the Center, and fathered one son and two daughters. The son, named Inyeol, was appointed to the Seventh Rank through hereditary privilege; the others remain young. The Assistant Mayor married the daughter of Kang Seokdeok, Director of the Court of Celestial Secrets, and fathered five sons and one daughter. The Vice President married the daughter of Choe Yun, Assistant Mayor, and fathered three sons and one daughter, all young. The Keeper of the Wardrobe bore one daughter who married Yun Lin, Grand Judge—a family likewise of good standing and long service.

    The epitaph says:

    The forebears of Park
    Descended from heaven of old,
    Their lineage deep and long—
    Generation upon generation of noble hearts.
    They shone throughout the Three Hans,
    But Milsan bore the brightest star.

    The Minister of the Board of Rites was kind and generous,
    Matching the ancients in his virtue.
    He labored for his posterity,
    Scattering blessings like falling rain.
    The Chancellor's giving was abundant
    Yet his rewards seemed slight,
    Yet through him the realm found order.

    Our Lord's birth was strange and wondrous—
    The dream of the ox, an auspicious sign!
    The Chancellor read the omen true:
    "This child shall restore our house."
    His virtue mounted high, his fame grew bright,
    His name inscribed in the rolls of merit.

    Filial and reverent in serving his parents,
    Generous and tolerant toward all men,
    He proved his loyalty to the throne.
    When traitorous officials once ran rampant,
    Spreading poison and chaos through the court,
    The sovereign swept away their treachery,
    And our Lord, standing at his side,
    Gained renown that shall not fade.

    Even as his honors rose,
    His heart grew ever more humble.
    Thus he found peace and ease,
    His spirit calm and untroubled,
    Shunning excess, embracing restraint,
    Leaving wisdom for his descendants.

    Yet virtue does not always bring long life—
    In his prime he departed this world.
    Gazing up at the boundless sky,
    We see his line continues:
    His worthy descendants stand thick as reeds
    Within his household's sacred gate.
    Our Lord remains eternal.

    Now we engrave these words upon stone
    That their radiance shall endure,
    And his virtue shine with the realm,
    Unending as the ages themselves.
